    <title>Combined summary - Bitcoin Core maintainers and communication on merge decisions</title>
    <updated>2023-06-16T17:41:57.423333+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2023-April/021565.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin Core project has been facing communication challenges for some time. One of the main issues is that maintainers merge pull requests without providing any commentary on their decision-making process. This lack of transparency and accountability has led to poor communication and delays in merging PRs. It has also resulted in contentious soft fork activation attempts, such as the CTV Pull Request, which was ultimately called off at the last minute.Another issue is that there seems to be inconsistency in the requirements for becoming a maintainer, leading to concerns from members within the community. However, some argue that requiring explanations for every merge would increase the burden on maintainers and lead to burnout. The shortage of maintainers has also resulted in delays in merging PRs. Additionally, there are concerns about governance and decision-making processes within the project. The recent blocking of potential maintainer Vasil Dimov raised questions about whether contributors have a voice in the decision-making process. Michael Folkson suggests that democratic institutions may not be a good fit for highly technical software projects. Therefore, there is a need for more transparency and accountability in merge decisions to prevent outright malicious actors from interfering with the project.Despite these challenges, there are alternative ways for developers to propose and implement changes, and competition and collaboration among developers can lead to better outcomes for the Bitcoin community as a whole. Bip 119 and bip 118 are two potential solutions for certain use cases. If these issues persist, it may be necessary to invest more heavily in consensus-compatible forks of Core.In terms of potential solutions, maintaining transparency and accountability is crucial for the success of Bitcoin Core. There is a need for more public collaboration and discussion, as well as the involvement of more anonymous or pseudonymous maintainers. Suggestions have also been made for better work practices, such as having individuals from different time zones involved in the development process. Furthermore, there is a need to establish clear guidelines and protocols for managing conflicts and disputes within the open-source community. The recent incident involving the removal of a key maintainer from an open-source project highlights the need for greater accountability and transparency within the community. To ensure that maintainers are treated fairly and consistently, mechanisms should be put in place to promote transparency and prevent abuses of power by existing maintainers.Overall, the Bitcoin Core project faces significant challenges related to communication, governance, and decision-making processes. However, there is also a sense of momentum towards increased collaboration and openness, with many developers proposing potential solutions and emphasizing the need for more transparency and accountability in merge decisions.</summary>
